postcontent: I purchased this Remington 541-T Sporter .22LR new in the early 1990's.  The rifle is in very good condition.  The walnut stock is a very nice straight-grain with ebony tip.  The blued-steel is excellent with just a couple of handling marks about 2" from the muzzle.  Comes with Leupold base and rings and is mounted with a Nikon Buckmasters 3-9x40mm scope in matte finish.  The scope has no blemishes of any kind.  Comes with one 5-round magazine.The walnut stock has several small blemishes but nothing major.  It's a very nice 3-footer, but the closer you look, you will see some small marks.  I'm just being totally honest, as that is always the best course.  There is a little patina on the trigger guard.  Like all 541-T rifles, this one is a tack driver.  Years ago I remember shooting a 50-yard 10-shot group that was one ragged hole.  But the rifle has not been fired in probably 5 years and it's time for someone else to enjoy it.  Both of my kids shot the 541 when they were growing up, but it's now a safe queen.I have only two trade interests, and I prefer to trade the rifle.  First, I'm looking for a good quality AR in 223/5.56 with a high-quality lined barrel in 1:9 twist or less.  And second, I would trade for an M&P Shield 9mm and you add cash.  I can add cash for the right AR.  And if you don't want the Nikon scope, we can work a deal without it.  If you want to buy it outright, just shoot be an offer.  These rifles are very rare, and I pretty much know what it's worth.Let me know what you have.  And I can send you a dozen hi-resolution photos, so just ask.  Thanks.
